&lt;h1 id=&#34;UDP (User Datagram Protocol)&#34; class=&#34;active&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34;  href=&#34;#UDP (User Datagram Protocol)&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;UDP (User Datagram Protocol)&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;UDP and its Features&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;UDP is a Transport layer protocol&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;It provides unreliable data delivery services
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Connectionless transport service
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;No guarantee packets received at all&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;No error checking, no sequencing, no flow control
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;No assurance packets received correctly and in correct sequence&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Lower overhead than TCP&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Lacks sophistication = simple
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;More efficient than TCP&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Useful situations
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Great volume of data transferred quickly, e.g., video streaming&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;2&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Format of UDP Messages&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Each UDP message is called a &lt;strong&gt;user datagram&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Has a fixed size header of 8 bytes&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;16 bit SOURCE / DESTINATION PORT fields
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Port number (between 0 and 65535)
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Well-known ports 0 ~1023&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Client hostâ€™s operating system may randomly choose a port  to communicate with a server&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Checksum is optional for IPv4, but mandatory for IPv6&lt;br&gt;
&lt;img data-src=&#34;https://cdn-fusion.imgcdn.store/i/2024/eaa62641752a90e7.png&#34; alt=&#34;UDPheader&#34;&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;3&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;UDP is used while error checking and correction are performed by the application, such as
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Domain Name System (DNS)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;IPTV&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Voice over IP (VoIP)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Real Time Streaming Protocol&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Routing Information Protocol (RIP)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

 &lt;h1 id=&#34;Routers and routing&#34; class=&#34;active&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34;  href=&#34;#Routers and routing&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;Routers and routing&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Routers&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A router joins two or more networks and passes packets from one network to another&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Routers can do the following:
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Connect dissimilar networks (LANs and WANs)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Interpret Layer 3 and often Layer 4 addressing&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Determine the best path for data to follow from point A to point B&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Re-route traffic if the path of first choice is down but another path is available&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Routers may perform any of the following optional functions:
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Filter broadcast transmissions&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Prevent certain types of traffic from getting to a network&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Support simultaneous local and remote connectivity&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Provide high network fault tolerance through redundant components such as power supplies&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Monitor network traffic and report statistics&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Diagnose internal or other connectivity problems and trigger alarms&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Categories of routers
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Core (interior) routers
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Direct data between networks&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;within the same autonomous system (AS)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Edge routers, or border routers
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;They connect an autonomous system with an outside network&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Exterior routers: any routers outside the organizationâ€™s AS
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Direct data between autonomous systems&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;2&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Routing tables&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Routing tableâ€”A database that maintains information about where hosts are located and the most efficient route to reach them
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Routers rely on them to identify which router is the next hop to reach a particular destination host&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Routing tables contain IP addresses and network masks
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A network mask identifies a network that a host or another router belongs to&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;3&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Static Routing vs Dynamic Routing&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Static routingâ€”Network administrators configure a routing table to direct messages along specific paths
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Exampleâ€”A static route between a small business and its ISP&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Dynamic routingâ€”Automatically calculates the best path between two networks and maintains this information in a routing table
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A router can detect problems with failed or congested routes and reroute messages through a different path&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;4&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Routing metrics&lt;br&gt;
Routing metricsâ€”Properties of a route used by routers to determine the best path to a destination:&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Hop count&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Theoretical bandwidth and actual throughput&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Delay, or latency, on a potential path&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Load, or the traffic or processing burden&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;MTU (maximum transmission unit) or the largest I P packet size in bytes allowable without fragmentation&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Routing cost, or a value assigned to a particular route&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Reliability of a potential path&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Topology of a network&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;5&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Determining the Best Routing Paths&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Routing protocolsâ€”Used by routers to communicate with each other to determine the best path&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Routers rate the reliability and priority of a routing protocolâ€™s data based on these criteria:
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Administrative distance (AD)â€”A number indicating the protocolâ€™s reliability&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Convergence timeâ€”Time it takes to recognize a best path in the event of a change or network outage&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Overheadâ€”The burden placed on the underlying network to support the protocol&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h1 id=&#34;Routing protocols&#34; class=&#34;active&#34;&gt;&lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34;  href=&#34;#Routing protocols&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;Routing protocols&lt;/h1&gt;
